Parses one fenced template-string body (the DSL used inside steno macro fences) into a `Vec<super::Chunk>` — the literal text, escapes, and `%`-operators that later get rendered/expanded. This is a hand-rolled recursive-descent character scanner, not a general parser combinator; all state lives in `TemplateParser` (char vec + cursor + source line for errors).

Entry point: `pub fn parse_template(src: &str, line: usize) -> Result<Vec<Chunk>, StenoError>`. `line` is only used to tag error messages with the fence's starting line; column is computed from the internal cursor (`col {i+1}`), so error text depends on both this file and whatever caller passes `line`.

Syntax handled, load-bearing and easy to get wrong when editing:
- `\n` and `\t` become dedicated `Chunk::Newline`/`Chunk::Tab` chunks (not literal characters); `\{ \} \% \| \\ \`` unescape to literal chars; any other `\x` is a hard error (`unknown escape \x`); trailing backslash at EOF errors too.
- `{` / `}` always become `Chunk::Brace{open}` chunks, never literal text — there's no escape-free way to emit a literal brace.
- `%` operators: `%0`-`%9` → `Chunk::Landing(digit)`, `%d` → `Dcount`, `%t` → `TypeSlot`, `%b` → `BodyBreak`, `%p` → `Pattern`. Anything else after `%` falls through to `take_block_operator`, which only recognizes `%[` (repeat) and `%(` (computed); any other `%x` is `unknown operator %x`.
- `%[ ... %]` is a repeat. Internally it parses a first segment stopping at either a top-level `|` or `%]`. If a `|` was hit, that first segment becomes the *separator* and a second segment (stopping only at `%]`) becomes the *body*. If no `|` appears, the single segment is the body and `sep` is empty — there is no way to specify a separator without a body-following-pipe. Unterminated `%[...%]` produces `unterminated %[ ... %]`.
- `%( expr )` reads raw characters up to a bare `)` (no nested-paren handling — the first `)` always closes it) and hands the substring to `super::expr::parse_expr`, wrapping success as `Chunk::Computed(parsed)`. A `None` from `parse_expr` becomes `bad computed expression "..."`; missing closing paren becomes `unterminated %( ... )`.

Coupling: `Chunk`'s variant set (`Lit`, `Brace`, `Newline`, `Tab`, `Landing`, `Dcount`, `TypeSlot`, `BodyBreak`, `Pattern`, `Repeat`, `Computed`) is defined in the parent `parse` module and consumed downstream by whatever renders chunks — any new operator added here needs a matching `Chunk` variant there. The computed-expression grammar itself lives entirely in `super::expr::parse_expr`; this file only extracts the raw substring.

`ChunkAcc` accumulates literal text and flushes it into a `Chunk::Lit` only when a non-literal chunk is pushed or at end of scan — adjacent literal characters are never split across multiple `Lit` chunks, and empty pending literal text never produces an empty `Chunk::Lit`.